        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat(qwen): add Token Plan (Team Edition) provider",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- OpenClaw's bundled `qwen` plugin already covers the Qwen Coding Plan, Standard pay-as-you-go, and the Portal/OAuth flow, but not the Alibaba Cloud Model Studio **Token Plan (Team Edition)**, a separate prepaid subscription that Alibaba steers coding and agent users toward. Today a Token Plan user has to hand-roll a custom provider.\n- This adds `qwen-token-plan` as a first-class provider in the same plugin, on the OpenAI-compatible gateway (`/compatible-mode/v1`), for both regions (Global / Singapore and CN / Beijing) selected by a base-URL swap.\n- Intended outcome: `openclaw onboard --auth-choice qwen-token-plan` (or `qwen-token-plan-cn`) yields a working provider with the full chat-model catalog and thinking, no manual config.\n- Intentionally out of scope: the plan's image-generation models (this is a text/vision chat catalog), and the gateway's Anthropic-compatible surface (we use the OpenAI-compatible one so the provider shares the rest of the qwen plugin's transport and thinking handling).\n- Success looks like: the provider lists its 12 models, authenticates with a Token Plan key, and reasons like the sibling qwen providers.\n- Reviewers should focus on the new provider wiring in `extensions/qwen` and the manifest additions (`providerAuthChoices`, `providerRequest`), since those are config-surface changes.\n\nThis keeps `bailian-token-plan` (the id Alibaba's own recommended OpenClaw config uses) working as a compatibility alias for `qwen-token-plan`, the same alias pattern `qwen-portal` / `qwen-cli` use for `qwen-oauth`.\n\n## Linked context\n\nWhich issue does this close?\n\nCloses #94418\n\nWhich issues, PRs, or discussions are related?\n\nRelated #26037 (Ali Bailian Coding Plan support; that is the Coding Plan, this is the Token Plan)\n\nWas this requested by a maintainer or owner?\n\nNo. This is a self-initiated contribution; I filed #94418 first, per issue-first.\n\n## Real behavior proof (required for external PRs)\n\n- Behavior or issue addressed: adds the Alibaba Token Plan as a selectable OpenClaw provider with its model catalog and reasoning, instead of requiring a hand-written custom provider.\n- Real environment tested: a real OpenClaw setup. Onboarded the CN (Beijing) Token Plan into an isolated `OPENCLAW_CONFIG_PATH` with a live `sk-sp-` key, then listed the provider's models through the OpenClaw CLI. Separately exercised the gateway directly with the same key (OpenAI-compatible surface) across the catalog.\n- Exact steps or command run after this patch:\n\n  ```\n  openclaw onboard --non-interactive --accept-risk --flow quickstart \\\n    --auth-choice qwen-token-plan-cn --qwen-token-plan-api-key-cn <redacted sk-sp- key>\n  openclaw models list --provider qwen-token-plan\n  ```\n\n- Evidence after fix (copied live OpenClaw output, key redacted):\n\n  ```\n  Updated config: /tmp/octp/openclaw.json\n\n  Model                                 Input      Ctx   Local Auth  Tags\n  qwen-token-plan/qwen3.7-plus          text+image 977k  no    yes   default,configured,alias:Qwen Token Plan\n  qwen-token-plan/qwen3.7-max           text       977k  no    yes\n  qwen-token-plan/qwen3.6-plus          text+image 977k  no    yes\n  qwen-token-plan/qwen3.6-flash         text+image 977k  no    yes\n  qwen-token-plan/deepseek-v4-pro       text       160k  no    yes\n  qwen-token-plan/deepseek-v4-flash     text       160k  no    yes\n  qwen-token-plan/deepseek-v3.2         text       160k  no    yes\n  qwen-token-plan/kimi-k2.6             text+image 256k  no    yes\n  qwen-token-plan/kimi-k2.5             text+image 256k  no    yes\n  qwen-token-plan/glm-5.1               text       198k  no    yes\n  qwen-token-plan/glm-5                 text       198k  no    yes\n  qwen-token-plan/MiniMax-M2.5          text       200k  no    yes\n  ```\n\n- Observed result after fix: OpenClaw onboarded the provider, resolved auth from the configured key (Auth = yes), and listed all 12 token-plan models with `qwen3.7-plus` as the configured default. Direct gateway calls returned HTTP 200 and streamed reasoning in the `reasoning_content` field for every model.\n- What was not tested: a live chat turn through a running gateway. The non-interactive onboard skips the gateway-health step without `--install-daemon`, so this config-only setup shows an expected `ECONNREFUSED` on the local gateway probe, and a chat turn would also consume plan credits. The capture above is the CN (Beijing) region; the Global (Singapore) path differs only by host.\n- Proof limitations or environment constraints: CLI and library behavior, so the evidence is copied terminal output rather than screenshots. The API key is redacted.\n- Before evidence (optional): N/A, this is net-new behavior.\n\n## Tests and validation\n\nWhich commands did you run?\n\n- `pnpm test extensions/qwen` (29 pass)\n- `pnpm test` for `src/plugins/provider-discovery.runtime.test.ts`, `src/plugins/contracts/registry.contract.test.ts`, `src/secrets/provider-env-vars.test.ts` (pass)\n- `pnpm tsgo:extensions` and `pnpm tsgo:extensions:test` (clean)\n- `oxlint` (extensions), `oxfmt --check`, `format-docs --check` (clean)\n\nWhat regression coverage was added or updated?\n\n- `extensions/qwen/provider-catalog.test.ts`: builder is `openai-completions`, region swap selects the right base URL, ships 12 reasoning-capable models, excludes image-generation models, and sets no hardcoded compat.\n- `extensions/qwen/index.test.ts`: registration declares the `bailian-token-plan` alias, the `QWEN_TOKEN_PLAN_API_KEY` env var, the two auth methods, and asserts the runtime auth choices match the manifest `providerAuthChoices` (so the interactive onboarding picker can list them).\n\nWhat failed before this fix, if known?\n\nN/A, this is a new provider.\n\nIf no test was added, why not?\n\nN/A, tests were added.\n\nNote on the suite: one unrelated test, `registry.contract.test.ts > covers every bundled web search plugin from the shared resolver`, fails on a clean `main` as well (it concerns web-search plugins, not this change).\n\n## Risk checklist\n\nDid user-visible behavior change? `Yes`. New provider and two new onboarding auth choices.\n\nDid config, environment, or migration behavior change? `Yes`. Adds the `QWEN_TOKEN_PLAN_API_KEY` env var, two `providerAuthChoices` entries, and two `providerRequest` family entries. All additive, no migration required.\n\nDid security, auth, secrets, network, or tool execution behavior change? `Yes`. Adds a standard API-key (Bearer) auth method and a new outbound gateway host, the same shape as the existing qwen providers.\n\nWhat is the highest-risk area? The config-surface additions (auth choices and `providerRequest` family), since they touch onboarding and provider discovery.\n\nHow is that risk mitigated? The additions are additive only and modelled exactly on the existing `qwen` and `qwen-oauth` providers. A new test locks the manifest auth choices to the runtime auth methods so they cannot drift.\n\n## Current review state\n\nWhat is the next action? Maintainer review.\n\nWhat is still waiting on author, maintainer, CI, or external proof? Nothing from the author. Happy to add a full in-app onboarding capture if that is wanted as proof.\n\nWhich bot or reviewer comments were addressed? None yet, this is the initial submission. An internal review pass before submitting added the manifest `providerAuthChoices` entries, the `providerRequest` family entries, removed a dead export, and added the manifest-vs-runtime auth-choice consistency test.\n\n---\n🤖 Generated with Claude Code (Claude Opus 4.8)\n🧑‍💻 Ideated, directed and reviewed by a human, @Omee11\n",
